Forensics Evidence Collection > [T1]: Lab - Evidence Collection: FTK Imager

4- Acquire different types of disk images using FTK Imager

FTK Imager is an impressive tool. You can use it to acquire a memory image, a triage image, and a disk image. In this part, we will see how we can acquire DISK images using FTK Imager. Once you run FTK Imager, you will be presented with the following view:

 

FTK Imager UI - (zoom in)

To create a disk image, click the "Create Disk Image" option from the file menu.

 

FTK Imager 'Create Disk Image' - (zoom in)

FTK Imager will ask you to select the type of disk image you want to acquire. Select "Physical Disk Drive".

 

FTK Imager 'Disk Image options' - (zoom in)

The next screen will ask you to select from existing physical drives connected to the machine. You will need to repeat the step for each disk if there are multiple disks.

 

FTK Imager 'Physical disks list' - (zoom in)

Click on Add button to set the destination.

 

FTK Imager "Image adding screen" - (zoom in)

Select the output image type.

 

List of images type - (zoom in)

  1. Raw (dd): a bit-by-bit copy of the original disk. Works with most tools.
  2. SMART: Linux ASR Expert Witness SMART tool image format. This image format isnt commonly used anymore.
  3. E01: EnCase image file format is the most commonly used imaging format. It stores metadata along with the image, such as case information, examiner name, notes, and MD5 hash.
  4. AFF: Advance Forensics Format open-source file format. Simson Garfinkel and Basis Technology developed it. The objective is to create an image format that does not lock the user into a proprietary format. This image format isnt commonly used.

You will use E01 as it is widely supported and has multiple helpful features we will discuss in the analysis phase.(eg.g, storing metadata, compression...etc.). Finally, you can add notes to save along the produced image.

 

Item Information screen - (zoom in)

  1. Case Number: used to track cases when you work on multiple cases.
  2. Evidence Number: assign a number for each piece of evidence related to the same case.
  3. Unique Description: additional details.
  4. Examiner: Will contain the analyst's name.
  5. Notes: additional notes you may want to add.

Clicking 'Next' will take you to another screen where you can specify the image's output location (This should be an external drive).

 

Image Destination - (zoom in)

  1. Click on Browse and specify the Image location.
  2. Set the image name.
  3. Image fragmentation: In case you want to save the output image into multiple files. For example, setting this to 1500 will break the output image into multiple files, 1500 MB each. 
  4. Select compression level. More compression means less disk space but more time.
  5. Encrypt the output image (optional).

Click "Finish" and return to the "Create Image" window.

 

Create image - (zoom in)

The remaining options are:

  1. Verify images after they are created: Used to calculate the hashes of the image and the original disk and compare them.
  2. Create directory listings: Used to create a txt file, including the files in the image.

Finally, click on start to begin the imaging process. FTK Imager will show the progress of as follows:

 

Creating image - (zoom in)

 

At the end of the process, FTK images will start verifying the output image (if this option was selected). 

 

Verifying - (zoom in)

The last screen is the verification result window.

 

Verification result - (zoom in)
